{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529442"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14418"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14418"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.77,0.06,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55286"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7113"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40813"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4651"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44419"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55286"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of paranoid delusions and auditory hallucinations. He was diagnosed with HIV five years ago but has been non-adherent to antiretroviral therapy for the past year. He has a history of depression and occasional cocaine use. He does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears agitated and disorientated. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. His CD4 count is found to be 50 cells/\u00b5L and his viral load is 500,000 copies/mL. Neurological examination reveals no focal deficits. A head CT scan shows no acute intracranial abnormalities. Urine drug screen is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Schizophrenia","AIDS-related psychosis","Substance-induced psychosis","Delirium","Major depressive disorder with psychotic features"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003EAIDS-related psychosis\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient presents with psychotic symptoms (paranoid delusions and auditory hallucinations) in the context of advanced HIV infection, as evidenced by his very low CD4 count (50 cells/\u00b5L) and high viral load (500,000 copies/mL). AIDS-related psychosis is more common in patients with advanced HIV disease and severe immunosuppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizophrenia\u003C/strong\u003E typically has an onset in late adolescence or early adulthood and a more gradual progression of symptoms. While it\u0027s possible for schizophrenia to present later in life, the context of advanced HIV makes AIDS-related psychosis more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstance-induced psychosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a consideration given the patient\u0027s history of occasional cocaine use. However, the urine drug screen is negative, and the duration of symptoms (two weeks) makes this less likely than AIDS-related psychosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelirium\u003C/strong\u003E can present with psychotic symptoms and is common in hospitalized HIV patients. The patient\u0027s disorientation and agitation could suggest delirium. However, the two-week duration of symptoms is more consistent with AIDS-related psychosis than delirium, which typically has a more acute onset and fluctuating course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMajor depressive disorder with psychotic features\u003C/strong\u003E is possible given the patient\u0027s history of depression. However, the predominance of psychotic symptoms over mood symptoms and the context of advanced HIV make AIDS-related psychosis more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that in a patient with advanced HIV presenting with new-onset psychosis, a thorough workup is necessary to rule out opportunistic CNS infections (such as toxoplasmosis, cryptococcal meningitis, or progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy) and other organic causes of psychosis. Treatment should focus on managing the psychotic symptoms, often with antipsychotic medications, while simultaneously addressing the underlying HIV infection with appropriate antiretroviral therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HIV-associated psychosis is more common in advanced stages of HIV infection with low CD4 counts.","Differential diagnosis of psychosis in HIV patients includes delirium, substance-induced psychosis, and opportunistic CNS infections.","Antipsychotic medications should be used cautiously in HIV patients due to potential drug interactions and side effects."],"references":["Nebhinani N, Mattoo SK. Psychotic disorders with HIV infection: A review. German J Psychiatry. 2013 Jan 1;16(1):43-8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40813"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14418"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40813"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T14:25:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T14:27:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7113"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55286"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"att